{{confused|Majorana fermion}} {{Infobox Particle | name = Majoron | image = | caption = | num_types = | composition = [[Elementary particle]] | statistics = [[Bosonic]] | group = [[Goldstone boson|Goldstone Boson]] | generation = | interaction = | particle = | antiparticle = | status = Hypothetical | theorized = Y. Chikashige, R. N. Mohapatra, and R. D. Peccei | discovered = | symbol = J | mass = unknown | decay_time = | decay_particle = | electric_charge = 0 ''e'' | color_charge = | spin = 0<ref> {{Cite journal |last=Lattanzi |first=M. |year=2008 |title=Decaying Majoron Dark Matter and Neutrino Masses |journal=[[AIP Conference Proceedings]] |volume=966 |issue=1 |pages=163–169 |doi=10.1063/1.2836988 |arxiv=0802.3155 }}</ref> | num_spin_states = }}
In [[particle physics]], '''majorons''' (named after [[Ettore Majorana]]) are a hypothetical type of [[Goldstone boson]] that are theorized to mediate the [[neutrino]] [[mass]] violation of [[lepton]] number or [[B−L|''B'' − ''L'']] in certain high energy collisions such as
: {{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|Electron}}&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|Electron}}&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;{{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|W boson-}}&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{SubatomicParticle|link=yes|W boson-}}&nbsp;+&nbsp;{{SubatomicParticle|Majoron}}
Where two [[electrons]] collide to form two [[W and Z bosons|W bosons]] and the majoron J. The U(1)<sub>B–L</sub> symmetry is assumed to be global so that the majoron is not "eaten up"{{clarify|date=December 2013}} by the gauge boson and spontaneously broken. Majorons were originally formulated in four [[dimension]]s by [[Y. Chikashige]], [[Rabindra Mohapatra|R. N. Mohapatra]] and [[Roberto Peccei|R. D. Peccei]] to understand neutrino masses by the [[seesaw mechanism]] and are being searched for in the neutrino-less [[double beta decay]] process. There are theoretical extensions of this idea into [[supersymmetry|supersymmetric]] theories and theories involving extra compactified dimensions. By propagating through the extra [[spatial dimension]]s the detectable number of majoron creation events vary accordingly. Mathematically, majorons may be modeled by allowing them to propagate through a material while all other [[Standard Model]] [[force]]s are fixed to an [[orbifold]] point.
== Searches == Experiments studying double beta decay have set limits on decay modes that emit majorons.
[[Neutrino Ettore Majorana Observatory|NEMO]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Arnold|first1=R.|last2=Augier|first2=C.|last3=Baker|first3=J. D.|last4=Barabash|first4=A. S.|last5=Basharina-Freshville|first5=A.|last6=Blondel|first6=S.|last7=Blot|first7=S.|last8=Bongrand|first8=M.|last9=Brudanin|first9=V.|last10=Busto|first10=J.|last11=Caffrey|first11=A. J.|last12=Cerna|first12=C.|last13=Chapon|first13=A.|last14=Chauveau|first14=E.|last15=Duchesneau|first15=D.|last16=Durand|first16=D.|last17=Egorov|first17=V.|last18=Eurin|first18=G.|last19=Evans|first19=J. J.|last20=Flack|first20=R.|last21=Garrido|first21=X.|last22=Gómez|first22=H.|last23=Guillon|first23=B.|last24=Guzowski|first24=P.|last25=Hodák|first25=R.|last26=Hubert|first26=P.|last27=Hugon|first27=C.|last28=Jullian|first28=S.|last29=Klimenko|first29=A.|last30=Kochetov|first30=O.|last31=Konovalov|first31=S. I.|last32=Kovalenko|first32=V.|last33=Lalanne|first33=D.|last34=Lang|first34=K.|last35=Lemière|first35=Y.|last36=Liptak|first36=Z.|last37=Loaiza|first37=P.|last38=Lutter|first38=G.|last39=Mamedov|first39=F.|last40=Marquet|first40=C.|last41=Mauger|first41=F.|last42=Morgan|first42=B.|last43=Mott|first43=J.|last44=Nemchenok|first44=I.|last45=Nomachi|first45=M.|last46=Nova|first46=F.|last47=Nowacki|first47=F.|last48=Ohsumi|first48=H.|last49=Pahlka|first49=R. B.|last50=Perrot|first50=F.|last51=Piquemal|first51=F.|last52=Povinec|first52=P.|last53=Ramachers|first53=Y. A.|last54=Remoto|first54=A.|last55=Reyss|first55=J. L.|last56=Richards|first56=B.|last57=Riddle|first57=C. L.|last58=Rukhadze|first58=E.|last59=Saakyan|first59=R.|last60=Sarazin|first60=X.|last61=Shitov|first61=Yu.|last62=Simard|first62=L.|last63=Šimkovic|first63=F.|last64=Smetana|first64=A.|last65=Smolek|first65=K.|last66=Smolnikov|first66=A.|last67=Söldner-Rembold|first67=S.|last68=Soulé|first68=B.|last69=Štekl|first69=I.|last70=Suhonen|first70=J.|last71=Sutton|first71=C. S.|last72=Szklarz|first72=G.|last73=Thomas|first73=J.|last74=Timkin|first74=V.|last75=Torre|first75=S.|last76=Tretyak|first76=Vl. I.|last77=Tretyak|first77=V. I.|last78=Umatov|first78=V. I.|last79=Vanushin|first79=I.|last80=Vilela|first80=C.|last81=Vorobel|first81=V.|last82=Waters|first82=D.|last83=Žukauskas|first83=A.|title=Search for neutrinoless double-beta decay of with the NEMO-3 detector|journal=Physical Review D|date=12 June 2014|volume=89|issue=11|doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.89.111101|bibcode = 2014PhRvD..89k1101A |arxiv=1311.5695}}</ref> has observed a variety of elements. [[Enriched Xenon Observatory|EXO]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Albert|first1=J. B.|last2=Auty|first2=D. J.|last3=Barbeau|first3=P. S.|last4=Beauchamp|first4=E.|last5=Beck|first5=D.|last6=Belov|first6=V.|last7=Benitez-Medina|first7=C.|last8=Breidenbach|first8=M.|last9=Brunner|first9=T.|last10=Burenkov|first10=A.|last11=Cao|first11=G. F.|last12=Chambers|first12=C.|last13=Chaves|first13=J.|last14=Cleveland|first14=B.|last15=Coon|first15=M.|last16=Craycraft|first16=A.|last17=Daniels|first17=T.|last18=Danilov|first18=M.|last19=Daugherty|first19=S. J.|last20=Davis|first20=C. G.|last21=Davis|first21=J.|last22=DeVoe|first22=R.|last23=Delaquis|first23=S.|last24=Didberidze|first24=T.|last25=Dolgolenko|first25=A.|last26=Dolinski|first26=M. J.|last27=Dunford|first27=M.|last28=Fairbank|first28=W.|last29=Farine|first29=J.|last30=Feldmeier|first30=W.|last31=Fierlinger|first31=P.|last32=Fudenberg|first32=D.|last33=Giroux|first33=G.|last34=Gornea|first34=R.|last35=Graham|first35=K.|last36=Gratta|first36=G.|last37=Hall|first37=C.|last38=Herrin|first38=S.|last39=Hughes|first39=M.|last40=Jewell|first40=M. J.|last41=Jiang|first41=X. S.|last42=Johnson|first42=A.|last43=Johnson|first43=T. N.|last44=Johnston|first44=S.|last45=Karelin|first45=A.|last46=Kaufman|first46=L. J.|last47=Killick|first47=R.|last48=Koffas|first48=T.|last49=Kravitz|first49=S.|last50=Kuchenkov|first50=A.|last51=Kumar|first51=K. S.|last52=Leonard|first52=D. S.|last53=Leonard|first53=F.|last54=Licciardi|first54=C.|last55=Lin|first55=Y. H.|l