'''Parbati Barua''' ({{lang-as|পাৰ্বতী বৰুৱা}}) is a citizen of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/the-elephant-princess-1617625.html|title=THE ELEPHANT PRINCESS|date=30 April 1995|publisher=|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.telegraphindia.com/1050313/asp/look/story_4480991.asp |title= Wild at heart |accessdate= 2007-06-26 |author= Anupam Bordoloi |publisher= The Telegraph (Calcutta, India edition) website |editor= Dr. Manas Pratim Das }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world/in-the-shand-of-time-he-left-his-mark-on-elephant-conservation-in-india/story-OMQqkpOnA0ld9gQ5i3SoQK.html|title=In the Shand of time, he left his Mark on elephant conservation in India|date=24 April 2014|publisher=|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> Born to Late Prakritish Chandra Barua of the [[Matiabag Palace|Royal Family Of Gauripur]] . She came to the limelight after the [[BBC]] created the documentary "[[Queen of the Elephants]]" based on her life, along with the companion book by [[Mark Shand]]. She resides in [[Guwahati]] and is also a member, Asian Elephant Specialist Group, [[IUCN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asesg.org|title=Welcome to the Asian Elephant Specialist Group|website=www.asesg.org|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> She is the sister of [[Pratima Barua Pandey]] and niece of [[filmmaker]] [[Pramathesh Barua]] of ''Devdas'' fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweekendleader.com/Culture/2081/lady-mahout.html|title=Lady mahout|website=www.theweekendleader.com|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>
